## The Full Vector Class

Here is the complete `Vector` class from `src/utils.js`. Every method you have seen across both lessons is here.

```js
class Vector {
  constructor(x = 0, y = 0) { this.x = x; this.y = y; }

  static zero()         { return new Vector(0, 0); }
  static one()          { return new Vector(1, 1); }
  static from(v)        { return new Vector(v.x, v.y); }
  static fromAngle(rad) { return new Vector(Math.cos(rad), Math.sin(rad)); }

  set(x, y)  { this.x = x; this.y = y; return this; }
  copy(v)    { this.x = v.x; this.y = v.y; return this; }
  clone()    { return new Vector(this.x, this.y); }

  add(v)   { this.x += v.x; this.y += v.y; return this; }
  sub(v)   { this.x -= v.x; this.y -= v.y; return this; }
  mul(v)   { this.x *= v.x; this.y *= v.y; return this; }
  div(v)   { this.x /= v.x; this.y /= v.y; return this; }
  scale(s) { this.x *= s;   this.y *= s;   return this; }
  negate() { this.x = -this.x; this.y = -this.y; return this; }

  normalize() {
    const len = this.length();
    if (len > 0) { this.x /= len; this.y /= len; }
    return this;
  }

  rotate(rad) {
    const cos = Math.cos(rad), sin = Math.sin(rad);
    const x = this.x * cos - this.y * sin;
    this.y   = this.x * sin + this.y * cos;
    this.x   = x;
    return this;
  }

  lerp(v, t) {
    this.x += (v.x - this.x) * t;
    this.y += (v.y - this.y) * t;
    return this;
  }

  length()       { return Math.sqrt(this.x * this.x + this.y * this.y); }
  lengthSq()     { return this.x * this.x + this.y * this.y; }
  dot(v)         { return this.x * v.x + this.y * v.y; }
  cross(v)       { return this.x * v.y - this.y * v.x; }
  distance(v)    { const dx = this.x-v.x, dy = this.y-v.y; return Math.sqrt(dx*dx+dy*dy); }
  distanceSq(v)  { const dx = this.x-v.x, dy = this.y-v.y; return dx*dx+dy*dy; }
  angle()        { return Math.atan2(this.y, this.x); }
  equals(v, e=0) { return Math.abs(this.x-v.x)<=e && Math.abs(this.y-v.y)<=e; }
  toString()     { return `Vector(${this.x}, ${this.y})`; }
}
```

In the next lesson we will use vectors as the foundation of our first engine class: the **SceneNode** transform.

## What Are Scenes?

As a game grows, managing its different states becomes a serious challenge. Without structure, you end up tracking mode with a pile of flags:

```js
let inMenu = true, inGame = false, isPaused = false;

function update(dt) {
  if (inMenu) { /* ... */ }
  else if (inGame && !isPaused) { /* ... */ }
  // This spirals quickly
}
```

A **scene** is a self-contained unit of game state. Each mode of your game is its own class:

- `MenuScene` — title screen, settings
- `GameScene` — the actual gameplay
- `PauseScene` — an overlay while gameplay is frozen
- `GameOverScene` — end screen, high score entry

### The SceneManager

`SceneManager` holds a registry of **init functions** — one per named scene. When you switch to a scene, it creates a fresh `Scene`, calls the registered init function to populate it with nodes, then starts the update loop. The previous scene is destroyed first if one is active.

```js
const sm = new SceneManager();

sm.register('menu', (scene) => {
  scene.addNode(new TitleLogo());
  scene.addNode(new StartButton());
});

sm.register('game', (scene, params) => {
  scene.addNode(new Level(params.level));
  scene.addNode(new Player());
});

sm.switchScene('menu');               // → creates Scene, runs init, starts loop
sm.switchScene('game', { level: 1 }); // → destroys menu scene, starts game scene

// In the game loop:
function tick(dt) {
  sm.update(dt);  // forwards dt to the current scene
}
```

`Scene` itself is never extended or instantiated directly — it is always created and managed by `SceneManager`.

## Setting Up a Scene

A `Scene` is a plain container for nodes — you never extend or instantiate it. Instead, you provide an **init function** to `SceneManager.register()`. When `switchScene` is called, `SceneManager` creates a fresh `Scene`, passes it to your init function, and starts the loop:

```js
sm.register('game', (scene, params) => {
  // Called once when this scene becomes active.
  // Populate the scene with starting nodes using scene.addNode().
  const player = new Player();
  player.position.set(300, 400);
  scene.addNode(player);

  const enemy = new Enemy();
  enemy.position.set(100, 100);
  scene.addNode(enemy);
});
```

There is no `start()` or `destroy()` to override on `Scene` — it is just a bag of nodes. All game logic lives in the nodes themselves.

### Adding and Removing Nodes Safely

Nodes can be added or removed *at any time*, including from inside another node's `update`. This is safe because of two internal queues:

- **`pending`** — nodes added during a frame are staged here and only enter `nodes` at the start of the *next* tick. This prevents a newly added node from being updated on the same frame it was created.
- **`pendingRemoval`** — nodes removed during a frame are staged here and fully destroyed at the start of the next tick. This prevents index-shifting bugs when splicing the live array mid-iteration.

```js
// Inside any SceneNode's update():
if (this.hp <= 0) {
  this.scene.removeNode(this);  // safe — deferred to next tick
}
if (this.canFire) {
  this.scene.addNode(new Bullet(this.position.clone()));  // also safe
}
```

## Scene Nodes — The Building Blocks

Every object in your scene **extends** `SceneNode`:

```js
class Player extends SceneNode {
  constructor(startPos) {
    super();  // auto-assigns id, sets up transform
    this.name = 'player';         // optional name for findNode()
    this.position.copy(startPos); // place in world
    this.speed = 200;
  }

  start() {
    // Called once when node enters the scene.
    // The node is fully live here — this.scene is set.
  }

  update(dt) {
    // Called every frame. dt = delta time in seconds.
    this.position.x += this.speed * dt;

    if (this.position.x > 700) {
      this.scene.removeNode(this);   // remove self
    }
  }

  destroy() {
    // Called when removed. Clean up event listeners, etc.
  }
}
```

### Nodes Can Talk to Each Other

Every node has a `scene` reference, so nodes can interact with their siblings:

```js
// Find a node by name:
const hud = this.scene.findNode('hud');
hud.showDamageEffect();

// Spawn a child:
this.scene.addNode(new Explosion(this.position.clone()));
```

### Auto-incrementing IDs

`SceneNode._nextId` is incremented each time a node is constructed, so every node gets a unique numeric `id`. This is useful for debugging and for systems that need to track nodes by identity rather than name.

## Transforms — Position, Rotation, Scale

Every `SceneNode` has a **transform**: three properties describing where it sits in space relative to its parent.

```js
const node = new SceneNode();

// Position — Vector — where is the node? (default: (0, 0))
node.position.set(100, 200);

// Angle — number in radians — how is it rotated? (default: 0)
node.angle = Math.PI / 4;    // 45° clockwise

// Scale — Vector — how is it stretched? (default: (1, 1))
node.scale.set(2, 1);        // twice as wide, normal height
```

All three are **local space** — relative to the parent node. A node with no parent is in world space directly.

### Transform ≠ Drawing

`SceneNode` does not draw anything by itself. The transform just describes *where and how* the node exists in the scene graph. A renderer (which we will build later) reads these transforms to draw sprites, shapes, or whatever the node represents.

### Connecting Vectors to Transforms

The Vector class you learned in the first two lessons is the foundation here:

```js
// Move a node along its facing direction each frame:
const facing = Vector.fromAngle(node.angle);
node.position.add(facing.scale(speed * dt));

// Point a node toward a target:
const dir = target.clone().sub(node.position);
node.angle = dir.angle();
```

Every vector concept — `add`, `normalize`, `scale`, `angle()`, `fromAngle()` — will appear in transform logic.
